  "prompt": "What happens to a photon after it hits the retina of my eye?",
  "response": "When a photon hits the retina of your eye, a series of biochemical processes are triggered in the photoreceptor cells (rods and cones) located there. Here\u2019s a step-by-step overview of what happens:\n\n1. **Absorption of Light**: The photon is absorbed by a photopigment in the photoreceptor cells. In cones, the photopigment is called opsin, which varies depending on the type of cone (S, M, or L for short, medium, and long wavelengths). In rods, the photopigment is called rhodopsin.\n\n2. **Isomerization**: Upon absorption of the photon, the chromophore (usually retinal) within the opsin changes shape (isomerizes) from a bent form (11-cis-retinal) to a straightened form (all-trans-retinal). This conformational change alters the properties of the photopigment.\n\n3. **Signal Transduction**: The isomerization of retinal triggers a cascade of biochemical reactions. This includes the activation of a G-protein called transducin, which, in turn, activates enzymes that lead to a decrease in the concentration of cyclic guanosine monophosphate (cGMP) in the cell.\n\n4. **Hyperpolarization**: As the cGMP levels fall, ion channels that are normally kept open by cGMP close, leading to hyperpolarization of the photoreceptor cell. This change in membrane potential affects neurotransmitter release.\n\n5. **Signal to Bipolar Cells**: The hyperpolarization of the photoreceptor reduces the release of neurotransmitters (like glutamate) at the synapse with bipolar cells. This change is interpreted by bipolar cells as a signal.\n\n6. **Further Processing**: The bipolar cells send signals to ganglion cells, which integrate inputs from multiple photoreceptors. The ganglion cells generate action potentials in response to the signals they receive.\n\n7. **Transmission to the Brain**: The axons of the ganglion cells form the optic nerve, which transmits visual information to the brain. The information is processed in the visual cortex and other areas, enabling you to perceive the light that entered your eye.\n\nUltimately, the photon that originally began this process has contributed to the complex experience of vision, leading to the perception of images, colors, and motion.",
